 DRACULA
Bram Stoker's Dracula

by Rod Pike, Remade Unofficially 2014 by Jon Bardi.

 PART 1: THE FIRST NIGHT
Here at last! The coach halts outside the Golden Krone hotel. It has been a scenic jouney if nothing else! Halfway across Europe through some of the most beautiful countryside I have ever seen. But it is a wild untamed landscape that seems only grudgingly to tolerate the coach tracks winding through it - like arteries, hurrying weary fares to their destinations, maybe even their destinies.. strange that I think that, but, as I leave the coach, the sinister fear of something unknown steals over me.....Bah! I am acting like a child! I must pull myself together. Here in the Carpathian mountains, I am a day's journey from my client's abode. But first some rest!! East lies the hotel.....

You can see a Coach driver.
> pay coachman

> pay coachman

Rudely taking the money that I offered, he strives off toward a small tavern at the end of the village, As i suspected, the man likes his liquor!!!
> e

> e

I am in the foyer of the hotel . It is a most intriguing place, adorned with the trim and trappings of mountain life.
Deers skins hang on the walls in a rather random fashion, mixed with the crafted leather harness and sleigh bells, adding a degree of rustic charm to the scene.
An ornate carved pine stair-case leads up to the bedrooms above.
Through a most picturesque arch-way to the East lies a dining room, while south leads to the reception desk. Westward, through a heavily timbered door, lies the road.

Flickering oil lamps cast shimmering pools of yellow light around the room, creating dark mysterious corners......corners where evil could hide and quietly fester, unseen until?...I must rest, my mind is overtired!!!
> s

> s

I am at the reception desk. Behind this is a small set of pidgeon holes for holding any mail for guests, beneath this is a row of timber pegs with keys to the guest rooms. Unlike European hotels, the desk runs from wall to wall with no access from the front. Instead, there is a rear entrance obviously for the use of the owners of the establisment.

> examine desk

> examine desk

The reception desk, like everything else is crudely fashioned, but solid. On it, a well worn register, adjacent to a small bell.
> ring bell

> ring bell

The bell rings a polite summoming call. The innkeeper shuiffles through the door behind the desk. He is poorly dressed, but clean and tidy. His attitude strikes me immediately as...humble?.....no!...his head is bowed, but when I catch sight of his eyes, I see....fear!

He speaks to me in a broken, almost apologetic English,
"You wish to stay with us yes?"
I reply that I do.
"Sorry I no speak English well, please to keep simple!"
I quickly grasp the man's level of understanding. "Yes!" I say, perhaps a little loudly. He turns and takes a key from a peg....
He seems to be waiting for me to do something.... The innkeeper stands behind the desk, holding a room key...
> sign register

> sign register

I sign my name with a well used quill.
He gives me the key. Barely looking up, "Your room is at the top of the stairs. Please, we hope you to be comfortable. The dining room I think is still serving if you require. Thankyou."
I thank him and he shuffles away.... There is a pathos about him which touches me deeply for some off reason..
