I am on the "UP line" platform. Shortly, a train pulls in.
I settle into my seat. As I journey on, I try to form a plan.
John's company in Stratford must have the destination of the boxes.
Then what? How does one secure boxes from the undead? And what, in the name of God, ARE the undead? One thing is certain, John was in earnest when he wrote, and I fear for humanity!

The train arrives at Stratford Station. I pass through the ticket office, to the street.
A cab pulls up.
"You look like a gent Sir, I knows all the companies round 'ere, better'n I know the road names! Who d'yer want ta visit?"

> hawkins

> hawkins

"Only five minutes away, Sir!"
I board the cab and after ten minutes, due to the Stratford traffic, we pull up. I give the man sixpence and tell him to keep the change.
"Thankyou Sir, a real gent!" Then he goes.

I enter Hawkins and Co. solicitors, and am greeted by Mr Hawkins...

"Dr Seward? Welcome!! I recieved your note today. Poor Jonathan, he has been through much!"

We talk for an hour and I give him all the facts. Then he says something which staggers me...

"Yes, I know where the boxes went. To your new neighbour at the Carfax Estate!"

My heart races. I leave immediately. While on the train, I recall a lecturer from my student days....Dr Van Helsing, of Amsterdam.
The occult was his hobby. I write a note explaining all, asking him to join me in England. I arrive back in Purfleet, posting my letter in the station postbox.
Then I leave the station.

The crossroads.
More of a junction really as the road only goes a little way North, while South is the rail-way ticket office...West leads through the village.

